We will evaluate this integral using integration by parts. The
integration by parts formula says that the following holds:

\begin{align*}
\int u\,dv = uv - \int v\,du.
\end{align*} If we let

\begin{align*}
u = \ln(x), \quad dv = \frac{1}{x^{7}}\,dx
\end{align*} then we have

\begin{align*}
du = \frac{1}{x}\,dx, \quad v = -\frac{1}{6}x^{-6}
\end{align*} and we can use
the integration by parts formula to write

\begin{align*}
\int \frac{\ln(x)}{x^{7}}\,dx &= \ln(x)\cdot \left(-\frac{1}{6}x^{-6}\right) - \int \left(-\frac{1}{6}x^{-6}\right)\frac{1}{x}\,dx\\
&= -\frac{\ln(x)}{6x^{6}} + \int \frac{1}{6x^{7}}\,dx \\
&= -\frac{\ln(x)}{6x^{6}} - \frac{1}{36x^{6}} + C
\end{align*} where $C$ is a constant of integration.

 Therefore,$\quad{\color{blue}\int \frac{\ln(x)}{x^{7}}\,dx = -\frac{\ln(x)}{6x^{6}} - \frac{1}{36x^{6}} + C
}$
